# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: warp-rust-web
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:warp-rust-web/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] In computer science, **function composition** is an act or mechanism to combine simple functions to build more complex ones.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Like the usual composition of functions in mathematics, the result of each function is passed as the argument of the next, and the result of the last one is the result of the whole.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Programmers frequently apply functions to results of other functions, and almost all programming languages allow it.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] In some cases, the composition of functions is interesting as a function in its own right, to be used later.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Such a function can always be defined but languages with first-class functions make it easier.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] The ability to easily compose functions encourages factoring (breaking apart) functions for maintainability and code reuse.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] More generally, big systems might be built by composing whole programs.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Narrowly speaking, function composition applies to functions that operate on a finite amount of data, each step sequentially processing it before handing it to the next.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Functions that operate on potentially infinite data (a stream or other codata) are known as filters, and are instead connected in a pipeline, which is analogous to function composition and can execute concurrently.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] For example, suppose we have two functions f and g, as in *z* = *f*(*y*) and *y* = *g*(*x*).
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Composing them means we first compute *y* = *g*(*x*), and then use y to compute *z* = *f*(*y*).
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Despite differences in length, these two implementations compute the same result.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] The second implementation requires only one line of code and is colloquially referred to as a "highly composed" form.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Readability and hence maintainability is one advantage of highly composed forms, since they require fewer lines of code, minimizing a program's "surface area".
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] DeMarco and Lister empirically verify an inverse relationship between surface area and maintainability.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] On the other hand, it may be possible to overuse highly composed forms.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] A nesting of too many functions may have the opposite effect, making the code less maintainable.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] In a stack-based language, functional composition is even more natural: it is performed by concatenation, and is usually the primary method of program design.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Which will take whatever was on the stack before, apply g, then f, and leave the result on the stack.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] See postfix composition notation for the corresponding mathematical notation.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Now suppose that the combination of calling f() on the result of g() is frequently useful, and which we want to name foo() to be used as a function in its own right.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] In most languages, we can define a new function implemented by composition.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] In languages such as C, the only way to create a new function is to define it in the program source, which means that functions can't be composed at run time.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] In functional programming languages, function composition can be naturally expressed as a higher-order function or operator.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] In other programming languages you can write your own mechanisms to perform function composition.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] using the built-in composition operator (.) which can be read as *f after g* or *g composed with f*.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] The first line describes the type of (.) - it takes a pair of functions, *f*, *g* and returns a function (the lambda expression on the second line).
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Note that Haskell doesn't require specification of the exact input and output types of f and g; the a, b, c, and x are placeholders; only the relation between *f*, *g* matters (f must accept what g returns).
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] where the parameter names are immaterial, as stated above.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Michal Ševčík credits CScalfani with a systematic exposition for function composition using additional parameters.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Variants of Lisp, especially Scheme, the interchangeability of code and data together with the treatment of functions lend themselves extremely well for a recursive definition of a variadic compositional operator.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Many dialects of APL feature built in function composition using the symbol `∘`.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] This higher-order function extends function composition to dyadic application of the left side function such that `A f∘g B` is `A f g B`.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Raku like Haskell has a built in function composition operator, the main difference is it is spelled as `∘` or `o`.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Also like Haskell you could define the operator yourself.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] In fact the following is the Raku code used to define it in the Rakudo implementation.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Nim supports uniform function call syntax, which allows for arbitrary function composition through the method syntax `.` operator.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Notions of composition, including the principle of compositionality and composability, are so ubiquitous that numerous strands of research have separately evolved.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] The following is a sampling of the kind of research in which the notion of composition is central.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Whole programs or systems can be treated as functions, which can be readily composed if their inputs and outputs are well-defined.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Pipelines allowing easy composition of filters were so successful that they became a design pattern of operating systems.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Imperative procedures with side effects violate referential transparency and therefore are not cleanly composable.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] However if one considers the "state of the world" before and after running the code as its input and output, one gets a clean function.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] Composition of such functions corresponds to running the procedures one after the other.
[src:warp-rust-web/function-composition-computer-science] The monad formalism uses this idea to incorporate side effects and input/output (I/O) into functional languages.
[src:warp-rust-web/latest-warp] warp is a super-easy, composable, web server framework for warp speeds.
[src:warp-rust-web/latest-warp] The main concept in warp is the `Filter`, which allows composition to describe various endpoints in your web service.
[src:warp-rust-web/latest-warp] Besides this powerful trait, warp comes with several built in filters, which can be combined for your specific needs.
[src:warp-rust-web/latest-warp] These specific filters will `reject` requests that don’t match their requirements.
[src:warp-rust-web/latest-warp] Take a look at the full list of `filters` to see what you can build.
[src:warp-rust-web/latest-warp] Testing your web services easily is extremely important, and warp provides a `test` module to help send mocked requests through your service.
[src:warp-rust-web/latest-warp] Convenient way to chain multiple path filters together.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
