[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:warp-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Tokio was released in August 2016 for Rust, a general-purpose programming language.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Developed by Carl Lerche, Tokio began as a network application framework and supports features such as socket listening and broadcasting, allowing messages to be transferred between computers.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Tokio began in August 2016 by Carl Lerche as a network application framework for Rust built on futures, allowing for network-based middleware and a non-blocking, or asynchronous, implementation of readiness interest to the reactor.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Tokio was inspired by Finagle, a Scala-based asynchronous remote procedure call (RPC) system developed at Twitter for Java virtual machines (JVM), allowing distributed systems to communicate within a JVM.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Tokio utilizes the lower-level Rust crate `mio`, itself using system calls such as epoll (Linux), kqueue (FreeBSD), and the input/output completion port (IOCP) API (Windows).
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] For Linux it can also use io_uring via tokio-uring.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] The name "Tokio" is derived from Tokyo and mio, and the Tokio logo vaguely resembles the city emblem of Tokyo.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] The preliminary version of Tokio was released in January 2017, followed by a full release in December 2020.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] In 2017, Tokio received a grant from the Mozilla Open Source Support fund.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] In April 2021, Tokio funded its first paid contributor, Alice Ryhl, for her work both developing the project and assisting its users.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] While Rust has supported asynchronous functions since version 1.39, released in November 2019, it provides no facilities to execute them, requiring an external runtime for that purpose.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Tokio provides a runtime that uses a multi-threaded work stealing scheduler.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Rust's futures are lazily evaluated, requiring functions to call `.await` before they do any work.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] When `.await` is invoked, Tokio's runtime may pause the original future until its I/O completes, and unpauses a different task that is ready for further processing.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Users of Tokio include the development teams behind Discord and AWS Lambda.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] The JavaScript and TypeScript runtime Deno uses Tokio under the hood, in comparison to the JavaScript runtime Node.js, which uses the libuv library.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Tokio allows for the execution of asynchronous functions in Rust through its built-in runtime, which may be initialized via the `#[tokio::main]` macro.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Here, the `reqwest` crate is used to request the HyperText Markup Language (HTML) for English Wikipedia.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] After `reqwest::get` is called to initialize the asynchronous request, `.await` will hand over control to the runtime, which then drives all the I/O operations of the request to completion before resuming the `main` function after the `.await`.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] This code makes use of the `tokio::spawn` function to create an asynchronous task (implemented as a stackless coroutine), allowing each connection to be handled separately in the same process, as the runtime ensures that tasks run in the background automatically.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Importantly however, the runtime multiplexes the tasks’ execution on a single thread pool (whose size is by default equal to the number of processors on the system), and so in comparison to the approach of spawning a separate thread for each task, fewer resources are consumed.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Tokio provides several I/O and timing primitives that work natively inside its runtime.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Tokio also provides several generic synchronization primitives suitable for use in an asynchronous context, including locks, semaphores, barriers and channels.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] Unlike the I/O and timer primitives, these work even outside of the runtime context.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] To facilitate interopability with traditional synchronous code, Tokio provides as part of its runtime a thread pool on which synchronous I/O operations may run.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] In particular, `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` creates a task which runs in this pool, and is allowed to perform blocking operations—this is unlike `tokio::spawn`, which may only run asynchronous code.
[src:warp-rust-web/tokio-software] For example, this is used to implement filesystem operations, as many platforms do not provide native asynchronous filesystem APIs (an exception to this is Linux's `io_uring`, however support for this exists only in the external `tokio_uring` library and is not yet built in).
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:warp-rust-web/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
